"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 12–14 (fill)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2kings-12-14-fill.py

Covers 72 missing verses: ch12 (20 missing; v9 exists), ch13 (24 missing; v20 exists),
ch14 (28 missing; v9 exists).

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 12: Temple repair under Jehoash of Judah — the two-stage reform (priests' failure, then
  Jehoiada's chest). The distinction between repair funds and cultic vessel funds (v13).
  Hazael's campaign against Gath and Jerusalem; the tribute payment as defensive diplomacy.
  Joash's assassination at Beth-millo — a rare royal murder in the Davidic line.
- Ch 13: Hazael's reduction of Israel's military to 50 horsemen/10 chariots/10k foot soldiers
  (v7) — the most precise military-reduction data in Kings, evidence of Aramean devastation.
  Elisha's deathbed sign-act: the bow-and-arrow oracle and the meaning of striking the ground
  three (not five or six) times. The post-mortem resurrection miracle at Elisha's grave.
- Ch 14: Amaziah's compliance with Deut 24:16 (not killing sons for fathers) as a legal
  milestone. The Valley of Salt and the capture of Sela. Joash's cedar/thistle fable as
  political wisdom literature. Jeroboam II's restoration of Israel's borders and the Jonah
  son of Amittai connection.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The synchronization formula — &lsquo;in the seventh year of Jehu&rsquo; — places Jehoash&rsquo;s accession within the dual-kingdom chronological framework. His forty-year reign is the longest of any Judean king in this section of Kings. The note that his mother was Zibiah of Beersheba is geographically significant: Beersheba, in the far south of Judah, suggests a non-Jerusalem, non-Davidic city connection for the queen mother — unusual in a court tradition that generally centered on Jerusalem. Jehoash had been hidden in the temple during Athaliah&rsquo;s six-year usurpation (11:3), making his survival a providential act that the temple itself embodied.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehoash&rsquo;s positive evaluation — &lsquo;he did what was right in the sight of the LORD all his days, for Jehoiada the priest instructed him&rsquo; (<em>kol-yāmāyw ʾăšer hôrāh yᵉhôyādāʿ hakkōhēn</em>) — is qualified by Jehoiada&rsquo;s continuing presence as the moral compass. This dependence on a priestly instructor means that Jehoash&rsquo;s faithfulness is institutional rather than personal. The 2 Chr 24:17–18 account makes explicit what Kings implies: after Jehoiada&rsquo;s death, Jehoash abandons YHWH. The priest&rsquo;s mentorship was the structural support for the king&rsquo;s righteousness; remove the support, remove the faithfulness.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The caveat &lsquo;nevertheless, the high places were not removed&rsquo; (<em>raḵ habbāmôt lōʾ-sārû</em>) appears formulaically for all Judean kings who receive a positive evaluation but fall short of complete reform — including Asa (1 Kgs 15:14), Jehoshaphat (1 Kgs 22:43), and Amaziah (2 Kgs 14:4). The high places were local sanctuaries where sacrifices and incense were offered to YHWH outside Jerusalem, technically violating Deuteronomic centralization law (Deut 12:2–7) but representing traditional practice that predated centralization. Their persistence is a standing indictment in the Deuteronomistic evaluation system even for otherwise faithful kings.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jehoash&rsquo;s temple repair initiative identifies three categories of consecrated funds: the &lsquo;census money&rsquo; (<em>kesep ʿōber</em>, the half-shekel head tax prescribed in Exod 30:11–16), &lsquo;personal redemption money&rsquo; (<em>kesep napšôt ʿerkô</em>, vow-based substitution payments per Lev 27), and free-will offerings (<em>kesep ʾăšer yaaleh ʿal leb-ʾîš</em>). These three revenue streams constituted the main income streams for temple maintenance; the fact that they had been diverted or mismanaged during Athaliah&rsquo;s reign made the repair urgent. The distinction between these categories matters: each had different legal rules governing its use.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The instruction that each priest should accept repair money &lsquo;from his own contacts&rsquo; (<em>ʾîš mēʾēt maqqārô</em>) — from his personal acquaintances or regular donors — created a decentralized fundraising structure tied to the priestly social networks. This peer-to-peer collection system was apparently the standard model before Jehoiada&rsquo;s reform. The priests were positioned as intermediaries between donors and the repair fund; they also had authority to authorize repairs as they found them, creating a dual role as fundraisers and disbursement agents that would prove problematic (v6–7).</p>",
    "6": "<p>By the twenty-third year of Jehoash&rsquo;s reign — nearly a quarter century into his rule — the temple repairs had still not been made. The failure is attributed to the priests who had not collected effectively or had not prioritized expenditure on repairs. The twenty-three-year delay creates the context for Jehoash&rsquo;s intervention: a reform that initially seemed straightforward required royal pressure to execute. The interval may reflect priestly inertia, competing claims on funds, or the practical difficulty of coordinating repairs in a functioning cult site.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jehoash&rsquo;s summons of Jehoiada and the priests — and his pointed question &lsquo;why are you not repairing the damage to the house?&rsquo; — is a rare instance of royal rebuke of the priesthood. The king exercises direct oversight over temple maintenance, a role that combined religious and administrative authority in the ANE royal ideology (cf. Solomon&rsquo;s construction of the temple in 1 Kgs 6). The solution Jehoash proposes removes the priests from the repair chain: they will no longer handle the repair funds or be responsible for the repairs (v8).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The priests&rsquo; agreement not to accept repair money and not to be responsible for repairs (<em>wᵉlōʾ-yᵉḥazzᵉqû ʾet-bedeq habbāyit</em>) is a formal negotiation of responsibility — a restructuring of the temple economy. By removing themselves from the repair chain, the priests trade revenue management for freedom from accountability. The shift from priestly management to royal oversight (through Jehoiada&rsquo;s chest, v9) prefigures modern notions of institutional segregation of collection and expenditure functions.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The collection procedure established by the chest — the king&rsquo;s secretary (<em>sōpēr hammelek</em>) and the high priest counting the money together — introduces a two-person verification system for financial oversight. Joint custody of the funds by representatives of royal and priestly authority is an ANE administrative best practice: dual oversight prevented misappropriation and provided accountability. The money was then &lsquo;weighed and counted&rsquo; (<em>wayyimᵉnû wayyāṣrû</em>), indicating careful measurement rather than approximate accounting.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The verified funds were paid directly to the construction supervisors (<em>mᵉqîmê mᵉlāʾkāh</em>, &lsquo;those who oversaw the work&rsquo;) who then disbursed to craftsmen — carpenters, builders, masons, stonecutters (vv. 11–12). The list of trades reflects the full range of skills required for temple repair in the Iron Age: woodworking, general masonry, specialized stone-cutting, and (v12) procurement of timber and dressed stone. This is a realistic inventory of construction labor specializations that matches the archaeological evidence for Iron Age building projects in the Levant.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The materials specified — timber (<em>ʿēṣîm</em>) and cut stone (<em>ʾabnê māḥāṣāḇ</em>) — were the primary building materials for the temple structures. Lebanon cedar had been used in Solomon&rsquo;s construction (1 Kgs 5:6–10); later repair periods used whatever timber was available, which might include local species. Cut stone (quarried and dressed) was required for wall repairs; the distinction from rough fieldstone (<em>ʾeben miqqāʿ</em>) indicates professional masonry that dressed stone to fit the existing structure. The phrase &lsquo;whatever was needed for the repairs&rsquo; (<em>lᵉkol ʾăšer-yēṣēʾ ʿal-habbayit lᵉḥizzāqāh</em>) suggests open-ended expenditure authorization rather than a fixed budget.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The explicit exclusion of silver and gold vessels from the repair fund — no basins, snuffers, bowls, or trumpets were made (<em>lōʾ yēʿāśeh bêt yhwh sipôt kesep mappuḥôt zᵉhāḇ</em>) — reflects a strict separation between repair funds and cultic vessel funds. The cultic vessels (musical instruments for worship, implements for the altar) were funded from different revenue streams — specifically the guilt and sin offerings described in v16. This distinction protects the integrity of both funds and ensures that the repair money is not diverted to ornamental purposes.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The closing statement that all the repair money went directly to the workers reflects the principle established in v11–12: the funds are entirely allocated to labor and materials, not to administrative overhead or priestly emoluments. This transparency of disbursement is noted approvingly by the narrator. The reform Jehoash and Jehoiada established represents a documented case of institutional reform in ancient Israelite temple administration — the first recorded instance of dedicated collection boxes for a specific purpose.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The non-requirement of financial accounting from the disbursement managers — &lsquo;they dealt honestly&rsquo; (<em>kî beʾemunāh hēm ʿōśîm</em>) — is stated not as naivety but as a mark of the workers&rsquo; character. In the ANE tradition, construction supervisors who dealt honestly with temple funds were considered to be acting in a sacred trust. The temple building inscriptions of Mesopotamian kings frequently boast of the honesty of construction managers; the note here places the workers in this tradition of sacred reliability. Jehoash&rsquo;s reform created the conditions (dual oversight, direct payment) in which honest workers could be trusted.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The guilt and sin offering funds were specifically reserved for the priests rather than the repair fund — a legal separation rooted in Levitical law (Lev 6:24–30; 7:1–7 specify that the flesh and parts of these offerings belong to the officiating priest). The narrative note confirms that Jehoash&rsquo;s reform preserved the priestly economic rights embedded in the sacrificial system even while removing the priests from the repair fund management. The reform was carefully calibrated: it changed the collection mechanism without disturbing the underlying priestly revenue structure.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Hazael&rsquo;s campaign against Gath — one of the five Philistine cities — represents a westward expansion of Aramean power beyond the traditional Israelite-Aramean conflict zone. Capturing Gath gave Hazael a position threatening the Shephelah corridor that led to Jerusalem. The phrase &lsquo;set his sights on going up against Jerusalem&rsquo; (<em>wayyāśem pānāyw ʿălôt ʿal-yᵉrûšālaim</em>) is the directional idiom of an advancing army; the threat to the Davidic capital would have been understood as a direct challenge to the covenant line.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehoash&rsquo;s response to the Hazael threat is to strip the temple and palace treasury of all dedicated gifts and tribute them to Hazael. The enumeration of previous dedicators — Jehoshaphat, Jehoram, Ahaziah — emphasizes that the treasury represented accumulated royal piety over generations; Jehoash is liquidating his predecessors&rsquo; devotional gifts to buy off the Aramean threat. This tribute diplomacy (<em>šālaḥ ʾet-kol-haqqodāšîm</em>) was standard ANE practice for smaller states facing stronger adversaries. The theological irony is that the temple treasures that Jehoash had worked to repair are now stripped to purchase Aramean withdrawal.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The archival reference to the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah closes the administrative section of Jehoash&rsquo;s reign. The selective nature of Kings is explicit here: the forty-year reign is compressed into a brief account of the temple reform and the Hazael tribute. The fuller record — presumably including military and administrative acts — is directed to the archival source. Kings is a theological narrative, not a comprehensive chronicle; it selects events that illustrate the theological judgments being traced.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jehoash&rsquo;s assassination by his own servants at Beth-millo — a place near or in Jerusalem, possibly a filled-in terrace fortification (cf. the Millo of 2 Sam 5:9) — is the violent end of the only Davidic king who had been hidden to escape Athaliah&rsquo;s purge. The conspiracy of servants against a king reflects the dangerous internal politics of the Jerusalem court. The route to Silla is otherwise unknown; the geographic specificity suggests access to a contemporary record of the event. Unlike the assassinations in the northern kingdom, this is the first royal murder within the Davidic line in Jerusalem.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The naming of the assassins — Jozachar son of Shimeath and Jehozabad son of Shomer (<em>yôzāḵār ben-šimʿāt wîhôzābād ben-šōmer</em>) — and their identification as servants (<em>ʿăbādāyw</em>) preserves what appears to be court archive information about a conspiracy that would otherwise be lost. The 2 Chr 24:25–26 account adds motivation: they acted in retaliation for Jehoash&rsquo;s killing of Zechariah the son of Jehoiada (the priest who had been his mentor and protector). Jehoash is buried with his ancestors in the city of David — the full royal burial despite his ignoble end.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The synchronization — twenty-third year of Joash of Judah — places Jehoahaz&rsquo;s accession in the wider timeline. His seventeen-year reign is relatively brief; the subsequent account concentrates on the devastation Hazael inflicted during this period. Samaria as capital is noted as the locus of Jehoahaz&rsquo;s reign — the northern kingdom&rsquo;s capital established by Omri (1 Kgs 16:24) continued to function as Israel&rsquo;s administrative center through this period.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The &lsquo;sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat&rsquo; (<em>ḥaṭṭôʾt yārābʿām ben-nᵉḇāṭ ʾăšer hēṭîʾ ʾet-yiśrāʾēl</em>) formula appears for every northern king in the Deuteronomistic evaluation. The specific sin is the golden calf cult established at Bethel and Dan (1 Kgs 12:28–29), which diverted northern Israelite worship from Jerusalem. The formula functions as a shorthand for the structural religious failure of the northern kingdom — the rejection of Deuteronomic centralization that the Deuteronomistic historian regards as the root cause of the north&rsquo;s eventual destruction.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The LORD&rsquo;s anger burning against Israel and giving them into the hand of Hazael and Ben-hadad is the covenant-judgment logic of Deuteronomy 28: military defeat as a consequence of covenant unfaithfulness. The Aramean dominance over Israel during Jehoahaz&rsquo;s reign represents the low point of Israelite power in the ninth-eighth century BCE — the kingdom was effectively reduced to a vassal or client state of Aram-Damascus during this period, which is confirmed by the Assyrian records of the period showing Hazael as the dominant power in the southern Levant.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jehoahaz&rsquo;s seeking of YHWH&rsquo;s favor (<em>wayyᵉḥal yᵉhôʾāḥāz ʾet-pᵉnê yhwh</em>) — using a verb of entreaty — is distinguished from formal covenant faithfulness. He does not reform the cult; he petitions YHWH in distress. YHWH&rsquo;s response — hearing because he &lsquo;saw the oppression of Israel&rsquo; (<em>rāʾāh ʾet-laḥaṣ yiśrāʾēl&rsquo;) — invokes the Exodus pattern: YHWH&rsquo;s rescue is motivated by compassion for the oppressed, not by the merit of the petitioner. This is one of the few instances in the northern kingdom narrative where YHWH responds positively to an Israelite king&rsquo;s prayer.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The deliverer (<em>môšîaʿ</em>) YHWH provides for Israel is not explicitly named here — some interpreters identify this as Jeroboam II (whose military restoration is described in 14:25–27) or possibly an Assyrian attack on Aram that diverted Hazael&rsquo;s pressure from Israel. The Assyrian king Adad-nirari III campaigned against Damascus around 803 BCE and is recorded in his own inscriptions as accepting tribute from &lsquo;the land of Omri&rsquo; (Israel) — a campaign that would have relieved Aramean pressure on Israel. If so, this is a case where YHWH&rsquo;s deliverance came through a foreign pagan empire, consistent with the Deuteronomistic theology of YHWH&rsquo;s universal sovereignty over nations.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Despite the military deliverance, the northern kingdom does not repent of the Jeroboam cult sins. The Asherah pole (<em>ʾăšērāh</em>) in Samaria that Ahab had installed (1 Kgs 16:33) remained standing — a permanent symbol of the Baal-Asherah syncretism introduced by the Omride dynasty. The persistence of the Asherah pole despite deliverances illustrates the structural nature of the northern kingdom&rsquo;s religious failure: individual kings might petition YHWH in crisis, but the institutional cult remained unreformed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The inventory of Israel&rsquo;s reduced military capacity under Jehoahaz — fifty horsemen (<em>ḥămiššîm pārāšîm</em>), ten chariots (<em>ʿăśāret rāḵāb</em>), ten thousand foot soldiers (<em>ʿăśeret ʾălāpîm raglî</em>) — is the most precise military-reduction data in Kings, preserved as a measure of Aramean devastation. Comparison with Ahab&rsquo;s military contribution at the Battle of Qarqar (853 BCE), recorded in the Assyrian annals of Shalmaneser III as 2,000 chariots and 10,000 soldiers, shows the catastrophic scale of the reduction: from 2,000 chariots to 10, from 10,000 soldiers to 10,000 (foot soldiers rather than a combined force). Hazael had effectively dismantled Israel&rsquo;s military capacity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The archival reference for Jehoahaz mentions his &lsquo;military exploits&rsquo; (<em>gbûrātô</em>, his acts of valor) alongside the general record of his reign. This is ironic: the king whose military was reduced to a fraction of its former strength is nonetheless credited with <em>gebûrāh</em> (valor, might) — either referring to the resistance he managed within the constraints of military reduction, or a formulaic tribute that acknowledges kingly duty regardless of circumstances. The Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel is cited as the authoritative source.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The death and burial formula for Jehoahaz — &lsquo;rested with his ancestors and was buried in Samaria&rsquo; — confirms Samaria as the northern royal burial site, distinct from the Davidic royal burial in Jerusalem (&lsquo;city of David&rsquo;). Burial in the capital city was the northern Israelite royal convention. His son Joash succeeding him maintains dynastic continuity in the Jehu line.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The synchronization for Joash of Israel — thirty-seventh year of Joash of Judah — is part of the double-synchronization system (kings synchronized with both the opposing kingdom and each other) that scholars have used to reconstruct the chronology of the divided monarchy. Joash of Israel&rsquo;s sixteen-year reign overlaps significantly with the later portion of Joash of Judah&rsquo;s reign, creating the coincidence that the same name (Joash/Jehoash) appears as king in both kingdoms simultaneously — a source of confusion that the text manages through careful synchronizations.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The standard negative evaluation formula for Joash of Israel — &lsquo;did evil in the sight of the LORD; he did not turn away from all the sins of Jeroboam&rsquo; — contrasts with the nuanced portrait about to emerge in vv. 14–19, where Joash mourns Elisha and receives a prophetic word about partial victory over Aram. The Deuteronomistic evaluation of northern kings is formulaic at the institutional level (the Jeroboam cult was never reformed) even when individual kings showed genuine piety in specific encounters with prophets.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Joash/Amaziah war (mentioned here in passing, elaborated in 14:8–14) is referenced in the archival formula as part of Joash&rsquo;s &lsquo;military prowess&rsquo; (<em>gbûrātô waʾăšer nilḥam ʿim-ʾᵃmazyāh</em>). From the northern perspective, Joash&rsquo;s defeat of Judah and breach of Jerusalem&rsquo;s walls was a major military achievement; the archival notice preserves this northern viewpoint.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The notice that &lsquo;Jeroboam sat on his throne&rsquo; before Joash&rsquo;s death is unusual — it may indicate a co-regency in which Jeroboam II began to reign while his father was still alive, a practice attested in both kingdoms for ensuring orderly succession. Joash&rsquo;s burial in Samaria &lsquo;among the kings of Israel&rsquo; (<em>ʿim-malkê yiśrāʾēl</em>) indicates a royal necropolis in the northern capital.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s final illness — &lsquo;the sickness from which he would die&rsquo; (<em>ḥolāh ʾet-ḥŏlî ʾăšer yāmût bô</em>) — is noted at the beginning of the deathbed account to signal its finality. Joash of Israel&rsquo;s visit to Elisha and his weeping with the cry &lsquo;My father, my father! The chariots of Israel and its horsemen!&rsquo; (<em>ʾābî ʾābî reḵeb yiśrāʾēl ûpārāšāyw</em>) exactly echoes Elisha&rsquo;s cry when Elijah was taken up (2:12). The formula &lsquo;chariots of Israel and its horsemen&rsquo; designates the prophet as the true military defense of Israel — more valuable than actual chariots and cavalry. Joash&rsquo;s use of this formula shows his recognition of what Israel is about to lose.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The bow and arrows (<em>qešet wᵉḥiṣṣîm</em>) that Elisha instructs Joash to take are weapons of active warfare — the prophetic sign-act will involve using them. Sign-acts (prophetically significant physical actions that represent and enact what they symbolize) are a consistent feature of the prophetic tradition: Jeremiah&rsquo;s linen belt (Jer 13), Ezekiel&rsquo;s brick (Ezek 4). Elisha&rsquo;s deathbed sign-act is his last prophetic act; it determines the scope of Israel&rsquo;s coming military success against Aram.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s placement of his hands on the king&rsquo;s hands during the shooting — the prophet&rsquo;s hands over the king&rsquo;s hands over the bow — transfers prophetic authority to the royal military act. The composite action (king draws the bow, prophet lays hands on) creates a joint symbol in which the prophetic power of YHWH is channeled through the royal military act. The east window pointing toward Aram across the Jordan is geographically precise: east is the direction of Ramoth-gilead and the Aramean territory.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s declaration — &lsquo;The LORD&rsquo;s arrow of victory, the arrow of victory over Aram!&rsquo; (<em>ḥēṣ-tᵉšûʿāh layhwh wᵉḥēṣ-tᵉšûʿāh bᵃʾărām</em>) — is the oracle that the sign-act enacts. The arrow shot eastward is not merely symbolic; it is the prophetic word that determines the military outcome. &lsquo;You shall strike down Aram at Aphek until you have put an end to them&rsquo; was the oracle&rsquo;s promise — a complete annihilation that would have reversed the devastation of 13:7. This promise, however, is qualified by what follows in v18–19.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The instruction to &lsquo;take the arrows&rsquo; and &lsquo;strike the ground&rsquo; — without specified number — gives Joash the opportunity to express his own interpretation of how thorough the coming victory will be. Striking the ground with arrows was apparently an oracle-determining act, where the number of strikes corresponded to the scope of the promised victory. Joash strikes three times and stops — a decision that, from Elisha&rsquo;s perspective, reveals inadequate resolve. Whether Joash stopped from politeness (not wanting to exhaust the dying prophet) or from genuine underestimation of what was possible, the result is a qualified oracle.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s anger (<em>wayyiqṣōp ʿālāyw ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) at Joash&rsquo;s three strikes — &lsquo;You should have struck five or six times; then you would have struck down Syria until you had put an end to it&rsquo; — is rare: a dying prophet openly rebuking a king for insufficient faith. The oracle&rsquo;s scope was determined by the human response to the prophetic instruction; Joash&rsquo;s restraint limited what YHWH had been prepared to give. The three victories that result (v25) are exact — neither more nor less than the number of strikes. This account functions as a theological teaching about how prophetic oracles interact with human agency and faith.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The post-mortem miracle at Elisha&rsquo;s grave — a dead man thrown into the grave touching Elisha&rsquo;s bones and coming to life — is the final miracle of the Elisha cycle, occurring after the prophet&rsquo;s death. It requires no prophetic word, no prayer, no sign-act: the contact with Elisha&rsquo;s bones is sufficient. This miracle is unique in the Hebrew Bible — a posthumous resurrection mediated by physical contact with a prophet&rsquo;s remains. The urgency (a raiding band approaching) explains the hasty disposal of the body into the nearest available grave. The detail serves multiple functions: it confirms that YHWH&rsquo;s power through Elisha was not diminished by death, and it provides a memorial to the prophetic significance of Elisha&rsquo;s ministry.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Hazael&rsquo;s oppression of Israel &lsquo;throughout the reign of Jehoahaz&rsquo; (<em>kōl-yᵉmê yᵉhôʾāḥāz</em>) is restated to frame the subsequent theological reflection in vv. 23–25. The severity of Aramean dominance — documented in the military reduction of 13:7 — becomes the backdrop against which YHWH&rsquo;s compassion and covenant faithfulness operate. The oppression is not minimized; it is presented as the full extent of the covenant curse for covenant unfaithfulness, which then creates the space for YHWH&rsquo;s gracious reversal.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theological axis of the passage: YHWH&rsquo;s grace toward Israel is grounded in the Abrahamic covenant (<em>lᵉmaʿan bᵉrîtô ʾet-ʾabrāhām yiṣḥāq wᵉyaʿăqōb</em>), not in Israel&rsquo;s faithfulness. This is the deepest covenant commitment in the Deuteronomistic framework: even when Israel fails, YHWH&rsquo;s covenant with the patriarchs constrains his judgment. &lsquo;He was not willing to destroy them (<em>wᵉlōʾ ʾābāh yhwh lᵉhašḥîtām</em>)&rsquo; — the divine unwillingness to annihilate his people is the bedrock on which the subsequent restorations rest, even when those restorations are temporary. The Abrahamic covenant functions as an unconditional floor below which judgment does not go.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Hazael&rsquo;s death and his son Ben-hadad&rsquo;s succession marks the end of the most dangerous phase of Aramean threat. Ben-hadad III (son of Hazael) is a weaker king whose reign corresponds with Assyrian pressure on Aram-Damascus; the Zakur inscription (an Aramaic stele from around 800 BCE) records a coalition against Ben-hadad that confirms his reduced power. The transition from Hazael to Ben-hadad represents a geopolitical opening that Joash of Israel exploits in v25.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s three victories over Ben-hadad — exactly three, matching the three arrow-strikes of v18 — are the precise fulfillment of Elisha&rsquo;s deathbed oracle. The cities recovered — those taken by Hazael from Jehoahaz — are not named here, but the restoration represents a partial recovery of the Transjordanian territory that Hazael had seized (cf. 10:32–33). The prophetic word has been fulfilled to the letter of what the human response determined: three victories, no more. Israel recovers significantly but does not achieve the complete annihilation of Aramean power that five or six strikes would have warranted.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>The synchronization — second year of Joash of Israel — places Amaziah&rsquo;s accession precisely in the dual-kingdom timeline. The name Amaziah (<em>ʾămasyāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH is mighty&rsquo;) reflects the Yahwistic devotion of the Judean royal naming conventions. His twenty-nine-year reign is in the middle range for Judean kings; it encompasses both military success (v7) and dramatic defeat (vv. 11–14).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The regnal formula — age (twenty-five), reign length (twenty-nine years), capital (Jerusalem), mother&rsquo;s name (Jehoaddan of Jerusalem) — follows the standard Judean template. The mother&rsquo;s name from Jerusalem is the opposite of the unusual Beersheba origin of Jehoash&rsquo;s mother (12:1); here the queen mother is specifically from the capital, indicating a court marriage. Mothers of Judean kings are consistently named in the regnal formulae; this reflects the queen mother&rsquo;s official court status (<em>gĕbîrāh</em>).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Amaziah&rsquo;s mixed evaluation — &lsquo;did what was right in the sight of the LORD, yet not as David his father had done; in all respects he followed the example of his father Joash&rsquo; (<em>raḵ lōʾ kᵉdāwîd ʾābîw kᵉḵōl ʾăšer-ʿāśāh yôʾāš ʾābîw ʿāśāh</em>) — positions him in a descending comparison: below David (the gold standard), equal to his father Joash. The Davidic standard is the benchmark that all Judean kings are measured against; only Hezekiah (18:3) and Josiah (22:2) approach it fully. Amaziah&rsquo;s faithfulness is genuine but incomplete.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The high places caveat appears for Amaziah as for most Judean kings who receive positive evaluations (cf. 12:3 for Jehoash). The persistence of high-place worship despite consistent royal piety indicates that the practice had deep cultural roots — it was the default worship pattern for most Israelites outside Jerusalem, continuing patriarchal traditions that predated the Deuteronomic centralization program. Removing the high places required not just royal will but a reformation of popular religious practice, which no king before Hezekiah achieved.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Amaziah&rsquo;s execution of his father&rsquo;s assassins — &lsquo;as soon as the kingdom was firmly in his grip&rsquo; (<em>wayᵉhî kaʾăšer ḥāzᵉqāh hammamlāḵāh bᵉyādô</em>) — indicates that he waited until his position was secure before taking the politically sensitive action of executing court servants. This prudent delay shows political sophistication; premature action against powerful court factions could have destabilized his early reign. The justice motive (avenging his father) is combined with the timing of political consolidation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The explicit citation of &lsquo;the Book of the Law of Moses&rsquo; (<em>bᵉsefer tôrat mōšeh</em>) in justification for not killing the children of the assassins is the first explicit legal citation in Kings since the early monarchy. The principle cited — &lsquo;parents shall not be put to death for their children, nor shall children be put to death for their parents; each person shall be put to death for their own sin&rsquo; (<em>lōʾ-yûmᵉtû ʾābôt ʾal-bānîm ûbānîm lōʾ-yûmᵉtû ʾal-ʾābôt</em>, Deut 24:16) — is individual criminal liability, which was counter to the ANE norm of familial solidarity in punishment. Amaziah&rsquo;s compliance with this Mosaic principle is presented as a mark of his faithfulness.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Valley of Salt (<em>gê-hammelaḥ</em>) was a valley south of the Dead Sea, the traditional battlefield for Israelite-Edomite conflicts (cf. 2 Sam 8:13, David&rsquo;s victory in the same valley). Ten thousand Edomites killed represents a significant military engagement. The capture of Sela (<em>hasseleʿ</em>, &lsquo;the rock&rsquo;) — traditionally identified with the later Nabataean city of Petra, though the identification is debated — and its renaming as Joktheel (<em>yoqtᵉʾēl</em>, meaning disputed) represents a symbolic act of Judean sovereignty over the captured stronghold. The continued name &lsquo;to this day&rsquo; indicates an ongoing place-name in the narrator&rsquo;s time.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Amaziah&rsquo;s challenge to Joash of Israel — &lsquo;Come, let us meet each other face to face&rsquo; (<em>lᵉkāh nîtrāʾeh pānîm</em>) — is a formal declaration of war couched in diplomatic language. &lsquo;Face to face&rsquo; is the idiom for direct military confrontation; the neutral language masks the aggressive intent. Amaziah&rsquo;s confidence after his Edomite victory may have led him to overestimate his position relative to Israel, which was simultaneously benefiting from Elisha&rsquo;s prophetic legacy and recovering military capacity after the Hazael years.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s counter-message to Amaziah — &lsquo;Yes, you have struck down Edom, and it has gone to your head (<em>wᵉnāśāʾ libbᵉḵā</em>). Be satisfied with your glory and stay home&rsquo; — is a direct piece of political wisdom: the king is correctly diagnosing Amaziah&rsquo;s overconfidence as the product of a limited victory. The warning &lsquo;why stir up trouble that will result in your downfall and that of Judah with you?&rsquo; is the counsel of an experienced pragmatist against reckless escalation. That the warning turns out to be prophetically accurate makes Joash&rsquo;s fable (v9) a form of unintentional prophecy.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Beth-shemesh (&lsquo;house of the sun&rsquo;) in the Shephelah was a border city between Judah and Israel — geographically appropriate for an Israelite-Judean conflict. The battle there represents an extraordinary reversal: Judah, which had just achieved a major military victory over Edom, is routed by Israel in a single engagement. The phrase &lsquo;every man fled to his home&rsquo; (<em>wayyānāsû ʾîš lᵉʾohālāyw</em>) indicates a complete military collapse rather than an organized withdrawal.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Judah&rsquo;s rout by Israel is stated bluntly — &lsquo;Judah was routed (<em>wayyinnāgepu</em>) by Israel&rsquo; — without explaining the tactical reasons for the defeat. The Deuteronomistic historian does not moralize explicitly about why Amaziah lost; the defeat follows his rejection of Joash&rsquo;s counsel (v11). The punishment for rejecting wise counsel is, in the narrative logic of Kings, the military consequence that follows. The 2 Chr 25:14–16 account adds a religious explanation (Amaziah&rsquo;s adoption of Edomite gods), which Kings does not include.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s capture of Amaziah at Beth-shemesh and his subsequent march to Jerusalem represents an extraordinary reversal of the normal political order: the northern king captures the southern king and attacks the Davidic capital. The breach of Jerusalem&rsquo;s wall &lsquo;from the Ephraim Gate to the Corner Gate&rsquo; — four hundred cubits (about 180 meters) — is a specific architectural detail that locates the breach in the northern section of Jerusalem&rsquo;s wall. The Ephraim Gate faced north, toward Ephraim (the northern kingdom) — the direction from which the attack came.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The stripping of Jerusalem&rsquo;s treasuries — temple gold, silver, and vessels, plus the palace treasury (<em>bêt hammelek</em>), plus hostages — is the same pattern of tribute-as-tribute that Jehoash had used to pay off Hazael (12:18). Now Jerusalem is on the receiving end of the same humiliation. The hostages (<em>bᵉnê thaʿărubôt</em>) served as guarantors against future aggression — they remained in Samaria as surety for Amaziah&rsquo;s good behavior. The looting of Jerusalem by a northern king is a theological shock: the Davidic city, which had survived Hazael&rsquo;s threat, has been breached by Israel.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The archival reference for Joash of Israel in v15–16 is the closing formula that the narrator has already anticipated in 13:12 — it is repeated here because the narrative of Joash&rsquo;s war with Amaziah required telling from the Judean perspective. The formulaic closure in both places brackets the Joash narrative from two different national perspectives. The mention of his &lsquo;military achievements&rsquo; (<em>gbûrātô</em>) specifically includes the war with Amaziah as a positive achievement from the northern perspective.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s burial &lsquo;in Samaria with the kings of Israel&rsquo; and his son Jeroboam&rsquo;s succession close the Joash account. The succession of Jeroboam II — who will reign for forty-one years (v23), the longest northern reign — marks a turning point in northern Israelite history. Under Jeroboam II Israel will achieve its greatest territorial expansion since Solomon; the prosperity and military success of his reign will become the object of Amos&rsquo;s prophetic critique.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The notice that Amaziah of Judah outlived Joash of Israel by fifteen years is chronologically important: the Judean king who was captured and humiliated by the northern king continued to reign after his captor&rsquo;s death. This temporal detail prevents the inference that Amaziah was deposed; he remained king, presumably under the constraints of the hostage arrangement and the loss of treasury resources. His fifteen additional years of reign were politically weakened, as the conspiracy against him (v19) eventually demonstrates.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The archival formula for Amaziah directs readers to the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah for the fuller account. The selective narration of Kings has focused on two events from Amaziah&rsquo;s reign: the execution of his father&rsquo;s murderers (vv. 5–6) and the disastrous war with Joash of Israel (vv. 8–14). The Edomite victory (v7) is mentioned briefly. The fuller record presumably included additional administrative and military acts.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Amaziah&rsquo;s assassination — the second royal murder in the Davidic line within two generations (cf. Jehoash in 12:20) — is preceded by a conspiracy that began in Jerusalem and forced him to flee to Lachish. Lachish (Tell ed-Duweir) was the second most fortified city in Judah after Jerusalem — a natural refuge for a king fleeing the capital. The conspirators&rsquo; pursuit to Lachish and the killing there suggests that the conspiracy had resources and persistence. The political instability of Amaziah&rsquo;s final years may reflect the lingering consequences of Jerusalem&rsquo;s humiliation under Joash.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Amaziah&rsquo;s body is returned to Jerusalem on horseback — a detail that distinguishes his burial (honored return to the capital) from his death (in exile). He is buried with his ancestors in the city of David — the full royal burial honors despite the ignominious end. The contrast between honorable burial and violent death is characteristic of the Kings narrative: even kings who die badly receive the formulaic burial honors if they were of the Davidic line.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&lsquo;All the people of Judah took Azariah (<em>ʿăzaryāh</em>) — also known as Uzziah — and made him king.&rsquo; The popular acclamation (&lsquo;all the people of Judah&rsquo;) bypasses any aristocratic succession mechanism; the people install a sixteen-year-old in direct response to the political vacuum created by Amaziah&rsquo;s assassination. Azariah/Uzziah will have a long and significant reign (2 Kgs 15:1–7; elaborated in 2 Chr 26), becoming one of the stronger Judean kings militarily. His name means &lsquo;YHWH is my strength.&rsquo;</p>",
    "22": "<p>Azariah&rsquo;s rebuilding of Elath (Ezion-geber on the Red Sea coast, modern Aqaba) restores Judah&rsquo;s access to the southern trade route that Edom&rsquo;s revolt under Jehoram had threatened (8:20). The Red Sea port had been valuable since Solomon&rsquo;s naval expeditions (1 Kgs 9:26–28); its recovery represents an economic and strategic restoration for Judah. The note that this happened &lsquo;after Amaziah rested with his ancestors&rsquo; suggests that the Elath project was one of Azariah&rsquo;s early achievements following his father&rsquo;s death.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Jeroboam II&rsquo;s reign — forty-one years in Samaria — is the longest of any northern king and one of the most significant periods of Israelite history, though the Deuteronomistic historian gives it minimal treatment (only seven verses). The eighth-century BCE was the peak of Israelite economic and territorial power in the divided-monarchy period; the Samaria ostraca (inscribed pottery shards from Jeroboam II&rsquo;s era documenting tax collections in wine and oil) and other archaeological evidence confirm the administrative complexity and wealth of this period. The Deuteronomistic narrative focuses on moral evaluation rather than political achievement.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The standard negative formula applies to Jeroboam II — he did not turn from the Jeroboam-I cult sins — despite the significant military achievements about to be described. The Deuteronomistic historian maintains the consistent evaluation principle: political or military success does not mitigate cultic unfaithfulness. The prosperity of Jeroboam II&rsquo;s reign, which the prophets Amos and Hosea critiqued as hollow because of social injustice and religious syncretism, is presented here through the same evaluative lens.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Jeroboam II&rsquo;s restoration of Israel&rsquo;s northern border from Lebo-hamath (the northern boundary of ideal Israel, associated with the pre-exilic vision of Israelite territorial extent, cf. Num 34:8) to the Sea of the Arabah (the Dead Sea) represents an unprecedented territorial reach for the northern kingdom. This expansion — in fulfillment of the word of the LORD through Jonah son of Amittai (<em>yônāh ben-ʾamittay hannābîʾ ʾăšer miggat-ḥēper</em>) — explicitly names the prophet Jonah, the same figure who is the subject of the canonical book of Jonah. Gath-hepher (modern Khirbet ez-Zurra in Galilee) was his home; this is the only extrabiblical chronological anchor for Jonah&rsquo;s ministry.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The motivation for YHWH&rsquo;s intervention on Israel&rsquo;s behalf despite their unfaithfulness — &lsquo;the LORD saw how bitterly Israel was suffering; there was no one left, slave or free&rsquo; (<em>wᵉrāʾāh yhwh ʾet-ʿŏnî yiśrāʾēl mōreh mᵉʾōd wᵉʾepes ʿāṣûr wᵉʾepes ʿāzûb wᵉʾên ʿōzēr lᵉyiśrāʾēl</em>) — echoes the Exodus motivations of divine compassion in the face of oppression. The phrase &lsquo;no one left, slave or free&rsquo; uses the Hebrew merism for totality (bonded and free representing all social categories) to indicate that the suffering had become total. YHWH&rsquo;s compassion for his people is presented as the ground for rescue even when their faithfulness does not warrant it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s stated unwillingness to blot out Israel&rsquo;s name (<em>lōʾ-dabbēr yhwh lᵉmaḥôt ʾet-šēm yiśrāʾēl mîttaḥat haššāmāyim</em>) parallels the earlier statement about the Abrahamic covenant in 13:23. The double theological statement — YHWH&rsquo;s covenant commitment to the patriarchs and his unwillingness to erase Israel&rsquo;s name — functions as the theological explanation for the anomalous prosperity of the northern kingdom during a period of continued cultic unfaithfulness. YHWH has not yet said the word that would terminate the northern kingdom; that word comes in 2 Kgs 17 after Jeroboam II&rsquo;s dynasty collapses.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Jeroboam II&rsquo;s recovery of Damascus and Hamath &lsquo;for Israel&rsquo; (<em>ʾăšer-hēšîb lᵉyiśrāʾēl ʾet-dammeśeq wᵉʾet-ḥamāt ʾăšer lîhûdāh bᵉyiśrāʾēl</em>) is a statement of extraordinary military reach — Damascus and Hamath had long been Aramean centers outside Israelite control. The phrase &lsquo;for Judah in Israel&rsquo; is textually difficult but may indicate that these territories were recovered as part of what had been ideally Israelite (united monarchy) territory. The archival reference again points to the fuller record in the Book of the Chronicles.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Jeroboam II&rsquo;s death formula — &lsquo;rested with his ancestors, the kings of Israel&rsquo; — and his son Zachariah&rsquo;s succession mark the end of the Jehu dynasty. Zachariah will reign only six months before being assassinated (15:8–12), triggering the period of rapid dynastic instability that leads to the Assyrian conquest. Jeroboam II&rsquo;s long reign is the last period of northern Israelite political stability; after him, Israel enters a terminal decline compressed into a generation. The prophetic critiques of Amos (c. 760–750 BCE) are set precisely in the prosperity of this reign, warning that its inequalities and cultic failures make it structurally unsustainable.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2kings', existing)
    for ch in ['12', '13', '14']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
